<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-733-630  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 733 630.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  August 1990 v13 n8 p39(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Supercomputer graphics: the market may not be as big as earlypredictions indicated, but it's still there.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gantz, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Market research firm Dataquest's current forecast of a $332million 1990 graphics supercomputer market is $170 million lowerthan early predictions because of several factors.andP;  These includethe merger of start-ups Stellar and Ardent who launched themarket, withdrawal of Evans andamp; Sutherland from the market and lossof 'short-term market momentum' by Apollo when acquired byHewlett-Packard Co. The market is rapidly growing, though, withprojected 1990 unit sales of 2,980 doubling 1989 sales.andP;  SiliconGraphics Inc is the market leader, as 1989 debut-year revenues forthe it's parallel-processing, reduced-instruction-setcomputer-based Power Series 4DGT systems quickly reached $150million.andP;  Market-driving factors include a decline in per-Mflopprices, low presence of international markets, a push forapplication development tools, and growing use of 3D modeling andvisualization.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Silicon Graphics Inc. (market share).andO;Ticker:    SGIC.andO;Topic:     Graphics SystemsSupercomputersMarket AnalysisTrendsGrowthApplicationsManufacturersOutlookRevenue.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphchart.andO;Caption:   The worldwide graphics supercomputer market. (graph)Graphics supercomputer vs workstations: application domains.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>